  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 6:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μὴ γνώτω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": in proverbial form a counsel to give with simplicity. Let not even thy left hand, if possible even thyself, know, still less other men; give without self-consciousness or self-complacency, the root of ostentation.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν τῷ κρυπτῷ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": known to the recipient, of course, but to no other, so far as you are concerned, hardly even to yourself. “Pii lucent, et tamen latent,” Beng.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ βλέπων ἐ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., who seeth in the dark. “Acquainted with all my ways.” Psalms 139, a comfort to the sincerely good, not to the counterfeits.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀποδώσει σοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": a certainty, and not merely of the future. The reward is present; not in the form of self-complacency, but in the form of spiritual health, like natural buoyancy, when all physical functions work well. A right-minded man is happy without reflecting why; it is the joy of living in summer sunshine and bracing mountain air. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν τῷ φανερῷ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 6:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 6:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a gloss by some superficial copyist, ignores the inward present reward, and appeals in a new form to the spirit of ostentation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
